==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*satjanan'', a causative of the base ''*set-'' ‘sit’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[settian]] (Dutch [[zetten]]), Old High German [[sezzen]] (German [[setzen]]), Old Norse [[setja]] (Swedish [[sätta]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌰𐍄𐌾𐌰𐌽]].  Compare [[sittan]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈset:an/}}

===Verb===
'''settan''' (class 1 weak: ''3 singular present'' '''[[sett#Old English|sett]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[sette]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[setton]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[sett]]''')
# to [[set]], [[establish]], [[place]], [[make]]
#:''Setton scyldas wið weal.''  They set their shields against the wall.  (''Beowulf'')

